-- t23 Accounting for Retirement Asset Distributions during the Decumulation Stage of Life -- t24 The Evolution of Financial Services in the Digital Age -- tPart IV: Future Directions -- t25 Behavioral Economics and Financial Decision Making -- t26 The Role of Socialization in Shaping Personal Finance Attitudes and Behaviors -- t27 Measuring and Applying Financial Literacy -- t28 Money Psychology: Beliefs and Behaviors about Investing, Saving, and Spending -- t29 Financial and Relationship Satisfaction -- t30 The Growing Role of FinTech and Robo-advisors -- t31 The Use of Financial Advice: Consumers’ Financial Advice-Seeking -- t32 The Future of Payments: Cash, Cryptocurrencies, and Peer-to-Peer Payments -- tPart V: Summarization -- t33 Personal Finance Research: An Editor’s Perspective -- t34 The Future of Personal Finance: An Educational and Research Agenda -- tList of Figures -- tList of Tables -- tAbout the Editors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe De Gruyter Handbook of Personal Finance provides a robust review of the core topics comprising personal finance, including the primary models, approaches, and methodologies being used to study particular topics that comprise the field of personal finance today. The contributors include many of the world’s leading personal finance researchers, financial service professionals, thought leaders, and leading contemporary figures conducting research in this area whose work has shaped—and continues to affect—the way that personal finance is conceptualized and practiced. The first section of the handbook provides a broad introduction to the discipline of personal finance. The following two sections are organized around the core elements of personal finance research and practice: saving, investing, asset management, and financial security. The fourth section introduces future research, practice, and policy directions. The handbook concludes with a discussion on an educational and research agenda for the future. This handbook will be a core reference work for researchers, financial service practitioners, educators, and policymakers and an excellent supplementary source of readings for those teaching undergraduate and graduate-level courses in personal finance, financial planning, consumer studies, and household finance.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mrz 2022) 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Finance / General.2bisacsh  aSaving, Investing, Asset Management, Household, Retirement.1 aAntonoudi, Efthymia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aArchuleta, Kristy L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAsebedo, Sarah D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBartholomae, Suzanne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBogan, Vicki L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChatterjee, Swarn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChatterjee, Swarn, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aChawla, Isha, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChien, Chia-Li, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChoi, Shinae L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCull, Michelle, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDiosdado, Leobardo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFan, Lu, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFox, Jonathan J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFurnham, Adrian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrable, John E.